<h1 class="doc-page-title">Product governance</h1>
<p class="doc-page-lead">Product governance is a comprehensive approach to tracking and managing Risks, Actions, Issues, and Decisions throughout their lifecycle.</p>

<h2 id="overview">RAID overview</h2>
                
                <p>RAID is an acronym standing for Risks, Actions, Issues, and Decisions. In COMPASS, we track three of these components plus Milestones:</p>

                <div class="row mt-4">
                    <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
                        <div class="card border-danger">
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <h3 class="h6"><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle text-danger"></i> Risks</h3>
                                <p class="small mb-0">Potential events or conditions that could negatively impact products or services if they occur. Risks are assessed by impact and likelihood.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
                        <div class="card border-primary">
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <h3 class="h6"><i class="fas fa-tasks text-primary"></i> Actions</h3>
                                <p class="small mb-0">Tasks or activities that need to be completed. Actions can be linked to risks, issues, milestones, or stand alone as general tasks.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
                        <div class="card border-warning">
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <h3 class="h6"><i class="fas fa-bug text-warning"></i> Issues</h3>
                                <p class="small mb-0">Problems or incidents that have already occurred and need resolution. Issues are tracked from identification to closure.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
                        <div class="card border-success">
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <h3 class="h6"><i class="fas fa-flag-checkered text-success"></i> Milestones</h3>
                                <p class="small mb-0">Significant events or goals in a product's lifecycle. Milestones can have associated risks, issues, and actions.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <hr class="my-4">

                <h2 id="risks">Risk management</h2>
                
                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">What is a risk?</h3>
                <p>A risk is a potential event or condition that, if it occurs, could have a negative effect on a product, project, or service. Risks are characterised by:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Uncertainty:</strong> It may or may not happen</li>
                    <li><strong>Impact:</strong> The severity of consequences if it does happen</li>
                    <li><strong>Likelihood:</strong> The probability of it happening</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Risk classification</h3>
                
                <h4 class="h6 mt-3">Risk types (multi-select)</h4>
                <p>Risks in COMPASS can be classified with multiple risk types simultaneously using checkboxes. This recognises that many risks span multiple categories.</p>
                
                <p class="small"><strong>Available risk types (13 standard categories):</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Strategy:</strong> Poorly defined or outdated strategic direction</li>
                    <li><strong>Governance:</strong> Weak oversight, unclear accountability, or poor governance</li>
                    <li><strong>Operations:</strong> Failures in internal processes or delivery operations</li>
                    <li><strong>Legal:</strong> Exposure to legal, regulatory, or contractual liabilities</li>
                    <li><strong>Property:</strong> Property, estate, or safety management deficiencies</li>
                    <li><strong>Financial:</strong> Ineffective financial control or value-for-money failure</li>
                    <li><strong>Commercial:</strong> Failures in contracts, suppliers, or commercial management</li>
                    <li><strong>People:</strong> Leadership, culture, or workforce capacity/capability issues</li>
                    <li><strong>Technology:</strong> Technology failures or insufficient system resilience</li>
                    <li><strong>Information:</strong> Data quality, availability, or misuse issues</li>
                    <li><strong>Security:</strong> Cyber, data, or physical security breaches</li>
                    <li><strong>Project/Programme:</strong> Programme or project delivery failures</li>
                    <li><strong>Reputational:</strong> Loss of stakeholder trust or public confidence</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="alert alert-info">
                    <p class="mb-0">You can select multiple risk types for a single risk. For example, a data breach might be classified as Security, Legal, Information, and Reputational risk.</p>
                </div>

                <h4 class="h6 mt-3">Risk tiers (governance levels)</h4>
                <p>Risks are classified by tier to indicate their governance level and scope:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Project-level:</strong> Tactical risks within a discrete project or service</li>
                    <li><strong>Programme-level:</strong> Risks across a set of related projects</li>
                    <li><strong>Portfolio-level:</strong> Risks across multiple programmes or business area</li>
                    <li><strong>Department-level:</strong> Strategic risks across the entire department</li>
                    <li><strong>Cross-government/systemic:</strong> Risks across multiple departments or sectors</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="alert alert-success">
                    <p class="mb-0">Risk tiers determine the appropriate governance body and escalation path. Higher-tier risks require senior oversight and approval.</p>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Risk assessment</h3>
                
                <p>Each risk is assessed using two dimensions:</p>

                <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-xxl-6 col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6 col-sm-12 col-12">
                        <h4 class="h6">Impact (1-5 scale)</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>1 - Very low:</strong> Minimal impact on delivery or outcomes</li>
                            <li><strong>2 - Low:</strong> Minor impact, easily manageable</li>
                            <li><strong>3 - Medium:</strong> Moderate impact requiring intervention</li>
                            <li><strong>4 - High:</strong> Significant impact affecting key objectives</li>
                            <li><strong>5 - Very high:</strong> Severe impact threatening success</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="col-xxl-6 col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6 col-sm-12 col-12">
                        <h4 class="h6">Likelihood (1-5 scale)</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>1 - Very low:</strong> 0-10% chance of occurring</li>
                            <li><strong>2 - Low:</strong> 11-30% chance of occurring</li>
                            <li><strong>3 - Medium:</strong> 31-50% chance of occurring</li>
                            <li><strong>4 - High:</strong> 51-80% chance of occurring</li>
                            <li><strong>5 - Very high:</strong> 81-100% chance of occurring</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="alert alert-info mt-3">
                    <p class="mb-0"><i class="fas fa-calculator"></i> <strong>Risk score:</strong> COMPASS automatically calculates the risk score as Impact × Likelihood, resulting in a score from 1 to 25. Higher scores indicate higher priority risks.</p>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Risk statuses</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Open:</strong> Risk identified and being monitored</li>
                    <li><strong>In mitigation:</strong> Actions are underway to reduce the risk</li>
                    <li><strong>Mitigated:</strong> Risk has been reduced to an acceptable level</li>
                    <li><strong>Accepted:</strong> Risk acknowledged but no mitigation action taken</li>
                    <li><strong>Realised:</strong> The risk has occurred (becomes an issue)</li>
                    <li><strong>Closed:</strong> Risk no longer relevant or has passed</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Risk ownership</h3>
                <p>Every risk must have an assigned risk owner who is responsible for:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Monitoring the risk and its likelihood/impact</li>
                    <li>Ensuring mitigation actions are progressing</li>
                    <li>Updating the risk status and information</li>
                    <li>Escalating the risk if needed</li>
                    <li>Communicating about the risk to stakeholders</li>
                </ul>

                <hr class="my-4">

                <h2 id="actions">Action management</h2>
                
                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">What is an action?</h3>
                <p>An action is a specific task or activity that needs to be completed. Actions in COMPASS can:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Be standalone tasks</li>
                    <li>Be linked to risks as mitigation actions</li>
                    <li>Be linked to issues as resolution actions</li>
                    <li>Be linked to milestones as delivery actions</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Action sources</h3>
                <p>Action sources track where actions originated from, enabling better traceability and reporting. This is particularly important for actions created by third-party assessors or external review teams.</p>
                
                <p class="small"><strong>Standard action sources:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Risk:</strong> Action created to mitigate, treat, or manage a risk
                        <ul class="small">
                            <li>Examples: Implement security controls, update procedures, conduct workshops</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Issue:</strong> Action created to resolve, workaround, or close an issue
                        <ul class="small">
                            <li>Examples: Fix bugs, restore service, implement workarounds</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Milestone:</strong> Action created to deliver a milestone or track progress
                        <ul class="small">
                            <li>Examples: Complete user research, deploy to production, deliver training</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Service Assessment:</strong> Action from service assessment review
                        <ul class="small">
                            <li>Examples: Address accessibility findings, implement security recommendations</li>
                            <li>May be created via API by external assessment platforms</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <div class="alert alert-warning">
                    <p class="mb-0"><strong>Note:</strong> Action source indicates the general origin category. Actions are also explicitly linked to specific risks, issues, or milestones via junction tables for full traceability.</p>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Action statuses</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Not started:</strong> Action created but work hasn't begun</li>
                    <li><strong>In progress:</strong> Work is underway</li>
                    <li><strong>On hold:</strong> Temporarily paused</li>
                    <li><strong>Complete:</strong> Action successfully completed</li>
                    <li><strong>Cancelled:</strong> Action no longer needed</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Action tracking</h3>
                <p>For effective action tracking:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Assign clear action owners</li>
                    <li>Set realistic due dates</li>
                    <li>Update status regularly</li>
                    <li>Add progress notes</li>
                    <li>Link to related RAID items</li>
                    <li>Close completed actions with summary notes</li>
                </ul>

                <hr class="my-4">

                <h2 id="issues">Issue management</h2>
                
                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">What is an issue?</h3>
                <p>An issue is a problem or incident that has already occurred and requires resolution. Issues differ from risks in that:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Risks</strong> are potential future problems (may happen)</li>
                    <li><strong>Issues</strong> are current problems (have happened)</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Issue classification</h3>
                
                <h4 class="h6 mt-3">Priority levels</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Critical:</strong> Severe impact requiring immediate attention</li>
                    <li><strong>High:</strong> Significant impact requiring urgent resolution</li>
                    <li><strong>Medium:</strong> Moderate impact, scheduled for resolution</li>
                    <li><strong>Low:</strong> Minor impact, can be resolved as resources allow</li>
                </ul>

                <h4 class="h6 mt-3">Severity</h4>
                <p>Issues are assessed for severity similar to risk impact assessment (1-5 scale).</p>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Issue statuses</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Open:</strong> Issue identified and logged</li>
                    <li><strong>In progress:</strong> Work underway to resolve the issue</li>
                    <li><strong>Waiting:</strong> Blocked or waiting on external dependency</li>
                    <li><strong>Resolved:</strong> Solution implemented, awaiting verification</li>
                    <li><strong>Closed:</strong> Issue fully resolved and verified</li>
                    <li><strong>Won't fix:</strong> Issue acknowledged but won't be resolved</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Issue lifecycle</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li><strong>Identification:</strong> Issue is discovered and logged</li>
                    <li><strong>Assessment:</strong> Priority and severity are evaluated</li>
                    <li><strong>Assignment:</strong> Issue owner is assigned</li>
                    <li><strong>Investigation:</strong> Root cause is identified</li>
                    <li><strong>Resolution:</strong> Solution is implemented</li>
                    <li><strong>Verification:</strong> Solution is tested and confirmed</li>
                    <li><strong>Closure:</strong> Issue is closed with documentation</li>
                </ol>

                <hr class="my-4">

                <h2 id="milestones">Milestone tracking</h2>
                
                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">What is a milestone?</h3>
                <p>A milestone is a significant point or event in a product's lifecycle, such as:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Project phase completions</li>
                    <li>Major deliverable due dates</li>
                    <li>Go-live dates</li>
                    <li>Review or approval gates</li>
                    <li>Funding decision points</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Milestone statuses</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Not started:</strong> Work hasn't begun toward the milestone</li>
                    <li><strong>In progress:</strong> Work is underway</li>
                    <li><strong>At risk:</strong> Milestone in danger of being missed</li>
                    <li><strong>Delayed:</strong> Milestone will not be achieved on time</li>
                    <li><strong>Achieved:</strong> Milestone successfully completed</li>
                    <li><strong>Cancelled:</strong> Milestone no longer relevant</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Linking RAID items to milestones</h3>
                <p>COMPASS allows you to link risks, issues, and actions to milestones to:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Track risks that could prevent milestone achievement</li>
                    <li>Document issues affecting milestone delivery</li>
                    <li>Monitor actions required to achieve milestones</li>
                    <li>Provide a comprehensive view of milestone health</li>
                </ul>

                <hr class="my-4">

                <h2 id="workflows">Common workflows</h2>
                
                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Workflow 1: From risk to action</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li>Identify and log a risk</li>
                    <li>Assess the risk's impact and likelihood</li>
                    <li>Assign a risk owner</li>
                    <li>Create mitigation actions linked to the risk</li>
                    <li>Assign action owners and due dates</li>
                    <li>Monitor action progress</li>
                    <li>Update risk assessment as actions are completed</li>
                    <li>Close or accept the risk when sufficiently mitigated</li>
                </ol>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Workflow 2: When a risk becomes an issue</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li>Risk is realised (the feared event occurs)</li>
                    <li>Update risk status to "Realised"</li>
                    <li>Create an issue documenting what happened</li>
                    <li>Link the issue to the original risk for traceability</li>
                    <li>Assign issue owner and priority</li>
                    <li>Create resolution actions</li>
                    <li>Work through the issue resolution lifecycle</li>
                    <li>Close both the issue and the original risk</li>
                </ol>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Workflow 3: Milestone delivery</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li>Create the milestone with target date</li>
                    <li>Identify risks that could prevent achievement</li>
                    <li>Create actions required to achieve the milestone</li>
                    <li>Monitor risks and action progress</li>
                    <li>Log any issues that arise</li>
                    <li>Update milestone status as needed</li>
                    <li>Mark milestone as achieved when completed</li>
                    <li>Conduct lessons learned review</li>
                </ol>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Workflow 4: Issue escalation</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li>Issue is logged and assigned</li>
                    <li>Resolution attempts are unsuccessful</li>
                    <li>Issue priority is increased</li>
                    <li>Issue is reassigned to higher authority if needed</li>
                    <li>Additional resources or actions are allocated</li>
                    <li>Stakeholders are informed of the escalation</li>
                    <li>Resolution continues with increased focus</li>
                </ol>

                <hr class="my-4">

                <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices</h2>
                
                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">General RAID best practices</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Be proactive:</strong> Identify risks early before they become issues</li>
                    <li><strong>Be clear:</strong> Use descriptive titles and detailed descriptions</li>
                    <li><strong>Be specific:</strong> Link RAID items to specific products and owners</li>
                    <li><strong>Be current:</strong> Update statuses regularly to reflect reality</li>
                    <li><strong>Be connected:</strong> Link related RAID items for traceability</li>
                    <li><strong>Be accountable:</strong> Always assign clear ownership</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Risk management best practices</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Review the risk register regularly (at least monthly)</li>
                    <li>Reassess impact and likelihood as situations change</li>
                    <li>Create specific, actionable mitigation actions</li>
                    <li>Don't close risks prematurely - ensure genuine mitigation</li>
                    <li>Consider both threats (negative risks) and opportunities</li>
                    <li>Document assumptions and dependencies</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Action management best practices</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Make actions SMART (Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bound)</li>
                    <li>Set realistic due dates in consultation with action owners</li>
                    <li>Break large actions into smaller, manageable tasks</li>
                    <li>Add progress updates even for in-flight actions</li>
                    <li>Don't let actions languish - close or cancel them if no longer relevant</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Issue management best practices</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Log issues as soon as they're identified</li>
                    <li>Set priority based on actual impact, not just urgency</li>
                    <li>Document root cause analysis</li>
                    <li>Track time to resolution for continuous improvement</li>
                    <li>Review closed issues to identify patterns or systemic problems</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Communication best practices</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Keep stakeholders informed of high-priority RAID items</li>
                    <li>Use consistent terminology across the organisation</li>
                    <li>Provide context in descriptions - assume readers don't have background knowledge</li>
                    <li>Use reports and dashboards to communicate RAID status</li>
                    <li>Celebrate when risks are mitigated or issues are resolved</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="alert alert-success mt-4">
                    <h3 class="h6">Further reading</h3>
                    <p class="mb-2">Learn more about using RAID in COMPASS:</p>
                    <ul class="mb-0">
                        <li><a href="@Url.Action("UserGuide", "Documentation")">User guide</a> - Step-by-step instructions for RAID tasks</li>
                        <li><a href="@Url.Action("Reporting", "Documentation")">Reporting</a> - Using RAID reports and dashboards</li>
                        <li><a href="@Url.Action("DataModels", "Documentation")">Data models</a> - Technical details of RAID data structures</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

